--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
“Dub-yah” and his political war-machine have decided that it is a moral imperative for us to go to war with Iraq. So resolved in this decision are they, that Bush has said that he does not need the support of Congress to do this, nor does he need the support of the rest of the free world, including all of our allies.<br>
<br>
EVERYONE, from Germany to Japan, from Saudi Arabia to the UK, from Egypt to China, all say that there has to be a better way to solve the situation than to “kill ‘em all”.<br>
<br>
Back in 1991, when his dad decided that our armed forces needed a live fire training exercise (a.k.a. the Gulf War), I was in support of that. At the time, being a high school senior, I thought that was what needed to be done. We can’t let this dictator walk into whatever country he feels like and start taking over.<br>
<br>
As the years passed, and the true politics of that situation came into the forefront, most people will now agree that the Gulf War was less about the freedom of the people in Kuwait, and more about keeping the flow of oil as constant and uninterrupted as possible.<br>
<br>
Fast forward today.<br>
<br>
Now “Dub-yah” is beating on the war drum just like his daddy did, saying that Sadam is an “evil” man, and he has created an “axis of evil” and that the only way to truly be free on this planet is to blow him straight to hell. Bush says that we need to topple the government in Iraq and put a “democratic” one in its place.<br>
<br>
Ok, here is the /rant:<br>
<br>
1.        Who does George Bush think that he is? The last time I checked, the USA was a democracy. He can go to war WITHOUT the support of Congress?!?  I personally believe in the idea that no one person should have the ability to send American citizens into war without first making sure that a majority of the people in the nation agree that this is a good thing.  I agree that something needs to be done, but I do not agree that the only course of action is war.  If 5 of the people in your group say that pulling a Sand Giant at lvl 15 is a bad idea, and you do it anyway, your an idiot.<br>
<br>
2.        Does George Bush think that he is so high and mighty that he can just go marching American troops into another country and create total chaos and havoc, when the rest of the world says that there has to be another way?  If 5 of the people in your group say that pulling a Sand Giant at lvl 15 is a bad idea, and you do it anyway, your an idiot.<br>
<br>
3.        If George Bush decides that he will send American troops into Iraq with the intention of a military coup, without the support of the rest of the world, without the support of Congress, and without the support of &quot;We the People&quot;, isn’t that the same thing that Sadam did to Kuwait in 1991? I mean, let’s not pull punches and let’s compare apples to apples, the USA would be no better than Sadam.  Overthrowing the current political paradigm and replacing it with one that is more easily 'manipulated'.  Sounds like Benito Musilini (sp)...<br>
<br>
Being a professional risk manager, I assess situations to determine risk/reward and have learned to trust my gut instincts. Personally, I get a real bad feeling in my gut when I think about a war with Iraq. It’s not the right thing to do, it's not the best way to solve and eliminate the risk, and it will jeopardize the lives of millions of people unnessecarily(sp).<br>
<br>
If the Middle East de-stabilizes, and utter chaos becomes the political regime, we will be in a worse position than we are now. If you are afraid of Sadam getting chemical/biological/nuclear weapons, image how you will feel when there is no one at the helm in the Middle East, and folks like Osama (or Sadam's kids) have their finger on the button, or someone worse, and no one knows who, what, where, when, how or why.<br>
<br>
That’s my opinion, we are on the precipice of a global nightmare, and George W. Bush is at the helm.<br>
<br>
I am scared.<br>
<br>
Now I ranted, where is my solution?<br>
<br>
My solution is simple. We need to find &quot;one vision&quot;. We need to have the U.S. Government make a call-to-arms and complete the development of a totally renewable and reusable fuel source.<br>
<br>
How do we stop Sadam and Osama (and Osama's buddys in Saudi Arabia)? We end the dependancy of the world on oil. It's hard to fund the development of chemical/biological/nuclear when you have no money. <br>
<br>
It will be difficult to pay suicide bombers and terrorist cells, when the BILLIONS of dollars that these Middle Eastern countries make for their oil is gone, because &quot;we the people&quot; decided that we will NOT be in the back pocket of George Bush, the Middle East and their common link of &quot;Light Sweet Crude&quot;. <p><img src = "http://home.maine.rr.com/waassaap/newtag.gif""http://home.maine.rr.com/waassaap/New5.gif'></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/unoddaduma.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nodda Duma </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tin Can!!!</span><br>  Posts: 514<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/29/02 7:13:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1219.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_thumbsup.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: &gt; Re: Its probably hopeless  </span><hr size=1> Problem with that scenario is that America is a humanitarian country.  Give aid to foreign nations, feed the hungry, don't start wars..<br>
